\begin_layout Standard
The structure of the product can be elucidated by relating it to the structure
 of the dyadic monoid
\begin_inset LatexCommand cite
key "Ve-M04,Ve-T04"

\end_inset

.
 A monoid is just a group, but without inverses; composing two elements
 of a monoid simply gives another element of the monoid.
 The dyadic monoid is a free monoid generated by two elements 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, with with 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{2}=e$
\end_inset

, and no constraints on 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 Alternately, the dyadic monoid is the free monoid in two letters 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

; both presentations can be seen to correspond to a binary tree.
 In essence, the dyadic monoid consists of those moves that can navigate
 down an infinite binary tree.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this problem, the functions 
\begin_inset Formula $g(y)=y/(1-y)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r(y)=1-y$
\end_inset

 are the generators of the dyadic monoid.
 Explicitly, this is
\begin_inset Formula \[
A_{k+1}\left(y\right)=\begin{cases}
\left(A_{k}\circ g\right)\left(y\right)=A_{k}\left(\frac{y}{1-y}\right) & \mbox{\; for }0\le y<\frac{1}{2}\\
\left(A_{k}\circ r\circ g\circ r\right)\left(y\right)=A_{k}\left(\frac{2y-1}{y}\right) & \;\mbox{ for }\frac{1}{2}\le y\le1\end{cases}\]

\end_inset

Alternately, it can be convenient to work with the left 
\begin_inset Formula $L=g$
\end_inset

 and right 
\begin_inset Formula $R=r\circ g\circ r$
\end_inset

 transformations, with locations in the binary tree identified by navigating
 to the left or right, composing 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The functions 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{k}(y)$
\end_inset

 reach their extremal values 0, 1 at exactly the Farey fractions from the
 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

'th row of the Stern-Brocot tree.
 These may be obtained by following the movement of the endpoints 0,1 through
 successive iterations of 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{-1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 These navigate 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

up
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the tree; a point of occasional confusion can be avoided by keeping in
 mind that taking the inverse reverses the order of symbols, i.e.
 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(f\circ h\right)^{-1}=h^{-1}\circ f^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 For example, the third row of the Stern-Brocot tree is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{5}=L^{-1}\circ L^{-1`}\circ L^{-1}\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\;\frac{2}{7}=L^{-1}\circ L^{-1`}\circ R^{-1}\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\;\frac{3}{8}=L^{-1}\circ R^{-1`}\circ L^{-1}\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\;\frac{3}{7}=L^{-1}\circ R^{-1`}\circ R^{-1}\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\;\frac{4}{7}=R^{-1}\circ L^{-1`}\circ L^{-1}\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)$
\end_inset

, and so on.
 Note that the order seems 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

reversed
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 from the natural order in which one might be tempted to apply the transformatio
ns 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Of particular importance is that exponential of the potential, eqn 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:exp-V"

\end_inset

, is just half the derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\exp-V\left(?\left(y\right)\right)=\frac{A^{\prime}(y)}{2}\]

\end_inset

This is perhaps the most remarkable result of this development.
 That the Gibbs measure can be written as infinite product is no surprise.
 That repeated applications of the shift operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 can be represented as the iteration of a function comes as no surprise
 either.
 That 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is the proper form for the shift operator just follows from a study of
 the self-similarity properties of the Question Mark.
 However, the expression for the potential 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, as written out in eqn 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:exact-potential"

\end_inset

, seems opaque, and without particular significance.
 Here, the potential is revealed to be 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

not just some arbitrary function
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, but related to the shift itself, and, more deeply, to the inverse of the
 transfer operator for the system.
 This is examined in greater detail below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Several final remarks are in order.
 First, one has that the partition function 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\left(\Omega\right)=1$
\end_inset

.
 This is no accident, but was guaranteed by construction.
 Forcing the relationship 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Jacobian"

\end_inset

, together with the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $?(1)=1$
\end_inset

, ensured that all normalizing factors that might have appeared in 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\left(\Omega\right)$
\end_inset

 were in fact absorbed as an additive constant by 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 Explicitly, this scaling leads to the constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\log2$
\end_inset

 in eqn 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:exact-potential"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Caution should be used when evaluating eqn 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:piece-product"

\end_inset

 numerically.
 If preparing a graph, or numerically evaluating its integral, the product
 is best terminated after 
\begin_inset Formula $N\le\log_{2}h$
\end_inset

 iterations, where 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is the step size for the numerical integral.
 Using 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 larger than this bound will result in a very noisy sampling, resulting
 in numerical values that no longer resemble those of 
\begin_inset Formula $?^{\prime}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Modularity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The self-similarity transformation of the Minkowski measure resembles that
 of a modular form
\begin_inset LatexCommand cite
key "Apo90"

\end_inset

.
 That is, given a general Möbius transform of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $(ax+b)/(cx+d)$
\end_inset

, with integers 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c,d$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $ad-bc=1$
\end_inset

, the self-similarity of the Question Mark takes the form 
\begin_inset Formula \[
?\left(\frac{ax+b}{cx+d}\right)=\frac{M}{2^{N}}+\left(-1\right)^{Q}\;\frac{?\left(x\right)}{2^{K}}\]

\end_inset

for some integers 
\begin_inset Formula $M,N,Q,K$
\end_inset

, depending on the specific values of 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c,d$
\end_inset

.
 Differentiating the above, one readily obtains 
\begin_inset Formula \[
?^{\prime}\left(\frac{ax+b}{cx+d}\right)=\left(cx+d\right)^{2}\;\frac{?^{\prime}\left(x\right)}{2^{K}}\]

\end_inset

which is almost exactly the transformation rule for a modular form of weight
 2, and is spoiled only by the factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{K}$
\end_inset

.
 This suggests a conjecture: that there may be some holomorphic function,
 defined on the upper half-plane, for which the Minkowski measure is the
 limit of that function, the limit being taken a it's restriction to the
 real axis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This conjecture is best illustrated numerically.
 Take the product 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:piece-product"

\end_inset

, terminating it after a finite number of terms; then graph the reciprocal.
 The resulting graph fairly resembles what one would obtain, if, for example,
 one graphed the Dirichlet eta function along a horizontal line, not far
 above the real axis.
 The Dirichlet eta is a prototypical example of a modular form; that its
 also commonly written as an infinite product is also highly suggestive.
 These similarities bear further elucidation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Generalized Shifts
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Several generalizations of the Question Mark are possible.
 To properly define these, it is imperative to regain a clearer view of
 the lattice model methods.
 The ingredients to the above construction made use of a lattice 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

, whose states are encoded by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

, a lattice shift operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

, and a function 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 on the lattice, to define a probability: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Pr_{V}(\sigma)=\frac{1}{Z(\Omega)}\prod_{k=0}^{\infty}\exp\left(-V\left(\tau^{k}\sigma\right)\right)\]

\end_inset

A second important ingredient was to provide an explicit identification
 of lattice arrangements 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 with real numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 in the unit interval, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=x^{-1}\left(?\left(y\right)\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Putting these together lead to the form 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
P_{f}\left(y\right)=\frac{1}{Z\left(\Omega\right)}\prod_{k=0}^{\infty}f\circ A_{k}\left(y\right)\label{eq:defn-P_f}\end{equation}

\end_inset

The appearance of 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{k}$
\end_inset

 is explicitly governed by the mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=x^{-1}\left(?\left(y\right)\right)$
\end_inset

; that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{k}$
\end_inset

 is a representation of the shift operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau^{k}$
\end_inset

, for this particular mapping of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to real values.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is simply 
\begin_inset Formula $\exp-V$
\end_inset

, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
f\left(y\right)=\exp-V\left(x^{-1}\left(?\left(y\right)\right)\right)\]

\end_inset

The partition function 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\left(\Omega\right)$
\end_inset

 is re-introduced as a reminder that the product definition only makes sense
 when 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 has been scaled appropriately; that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is arbitrary only up to a total scale factor; 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 exists only as an element of a projective space.
 The constraint is even stronger: inappropriately normalized 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 lead to the formal divergence 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\left(\Omega\right)=\infty$
\end_inset

; there is only one normalization for which 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\left(\Omega\right)$
\end_inset

 is finite, and that furthermore, by construction, one then has 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\left(\Omega\right)=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Two directions along which to generalize are now clear: one may consider
 general functions 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, and one may consider different mappings from the lattice space 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 to the unit interval (which is compact, or to the positive real number
 line, which is not).
 The former is reviewed in a later section; lets treat the later case first.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The most widely used mapping is usually the much simpler one: 
\begin_inset Formula $x=x\left(\sigma\right)$
\end_inset

 from eqn 
