\begin_layout Section
The Transfer Operator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The mapping from the lattice to the unit interval results in a collision
 of effects coming from different topologies: the product topology of the
 lattice, and the natural topology of the real number line.
 A standard way of studying this collision is by means of the transfer operator.
 The goal of this section is to introduce the transfer operator; the next
 section will show, in general terms, that the transfer operator is the
 push-forward of the shift operator.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Transfer operators, also commonly called Perron-Frobenius operators or Perron-Fr
obenius-Ruelle operators, as formulated by David Ruelle[xxx need ref] are
 a commonly-used tool for studying dynamical systems
\begin_inset LatexCommand cite
key "Dri99"

\end_inset

.
 As the name 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Perron-Frobenius
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 suggests, these are bounded operators, whose largest eigenvalue is equal
 to one; the existence of this eigenvalue is commonly justified by appealing
 to the Frobenius theorem, which states that bounded operators have a maximal
 eigenvalue.
 The origin of the name 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

transfer
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 comes from lattice-model physics, where the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

transfer interaction
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

transfer matrix
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is studied
\begin_inset LatexCommand cite
key "Gutzwiller1990,Glimm1981,Kittel1976"

\end_inset

.
 In this context, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

transfer interaction
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 describes the effect of neighboring lattice sites on one-another; it can
 be seen to be a matrix when the number of interacting lattice sites, and
 the number states a single lattice point can be in, is finite.
 It becomes an operator when the interaction is infinite range, or when
 the set of states at a lattice site is no longer finite.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is easiest to begin with a concrete definition.
 Consider a function 
\begin_inset Formula $g:[0,1]\to[0,1]$
\end_inset

, that is, a function mapping the unit interval of the real number line
 to itself.
 Upon iteration, the function may have fixed points or orbits of points.
 These orbits may be attractors or repellors, or may be neutral saddle points.
 The action of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 may be ergodic or chaotic, strong-mixing or merely topologically mixing.
 In any case, the language used to discuss 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is inherently based on either the point-set topology of the unit interval,
 or the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

natural
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 topology on the unit interval, the topology of open sets.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A shift in perspective may be gained not by considering how 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 acts on points or open sets, but instead by considering how 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 acts on distributions on the unit interval.
 Intuitively, one might consider a dusting of points on the unit interval,
 with the local density given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(x)$
\end_inset

 at point 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

, and then consider how this dusting or density evolves upon iteration by
 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 This verbal description may be given form as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\rho^{\prime}(y)=\int_{0}^{1}\,\delta\left(y-g(x)\right)\rho(x)\; dx\label{eq:transfer-dirac}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho^{\prime}(y)$
\end_inset

 is the new density at point 
\begin_inset Formula $y=g(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 is the Dirac delta function.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this viewpoint, 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 becomes an operator that maps densities 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 to other densities 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho^{\prime}$
\end_inset

, or notationally, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{g}\rho=\rho^{\prime}\]

\end_inset

The operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{g}$
\end_inset

 is the transfer operator or the Ruelle-Frobenius-Perron operator.
 It is not hard to see that it is a linear operator, in that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{g}(a\rho_{1}+b\rho_{2})=a\mathcal{L}_{g}\rho_{1}+b\mathcal{L}_{g}\rho_{2}\]

\end_inset

 for constants 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b$
\end_inset

 and densities 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{1},\rho_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the function 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is differentiable, and doesn't have a vanishing derivative, the integral
 formulation of the transfer operator 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:transfer-dirac"

\end_inset

 can be rephrased in a more convenient form, as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left[\mathcal{L}_{g}\rho\right]\left(y\right)=\sum_{x:y=g(x)}\frac{\rho(x)}{\left|dg(x)/dx\right|}\label{eq: transfer-jacobi}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the sum is presumed to extend over at most a countable number of points.
 That is, when 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is many-to-one, the sum is over the pre-images of the point 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Both of the above definitions are mired in a language that implicitly assumes
 the real-number line, and its natural topology.
 Yet clearly, this is of limited utility; extracting the topology from the
 definition provides a clearer picture of the object itself.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Push-Forward
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, it will be shown that the transfer operator is the push-forward
 of the shift operator; a theorem and a sequence of lemmas will be posed,
 that hold in general form.
 The point of this theorem is to disentangle the role of topology, and specifica
lly, the role of measure theory, from the use of the shift operator.
 We begin with a general setting.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, and a field 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 over the reals 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 may be taken to be 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 itself, or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

 or some more general field over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 The restriction of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 to being a field over the reals is is required, so that it can be used
 in conjunction with a measure; measures are always real-valued.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One may then define the algebra of functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(X)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 as the set of functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{F}(X)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to F$
\end_inset

.
 An algebra is a vector space endowed with multiplication between vectors.
 The space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(X)$
\end_inset

 is a vector space, in that given two functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1},f_{2}\in\mathcal{F}(X)$
\end_inset

, their linear combination 
\begin_inset Formula $af_{1}+bf_{2}$
\end_inset

 is also an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(X)$
\end_inset

; thus 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}$
\end_inset

 may be interpreted to be the vectors of a vector space.
 Multiplication is the point-wise multiplication of function values; that
 is, the product 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}f_{2}$
\end_inset

 is defined as the function 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{1}f_{2})(x)=f_{1}(x)\cdot f_{2}(x)$
\end_inset

, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}f_{2}$
\end_inset

 is again an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(X)$
\end_inset

.
 Since one clearly has 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}f_{2}=f_{2}f_{1}$
\end_inset

, multiplication is commutative, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(X)$
\end_inset

 is also a commutative ring.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(X)$
\end_inset

 may be endowed with a topology.
 The coarsest topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(X)$
\end_inset

 is the 
\emph on
weak topology
\emph default
, which is obtained by taking 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(X)$
\end_inset

 to be the space that is topological dual to 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 As a vector space, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(X)$
\end_inset

 may be endowed with a norm 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert f\right\Vert $
\end_inset

.
 For example, one may take the norm to be the 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{p}$
\end_inset

-norm 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left\Vert f\right\Vert _{p}=\left(\int\left|f(x)\right|^{p}dx\right)^{1/p}\]

\end_inset

For 
\begin_inset Formula $p=2$
\end_inset

, this norm converts the space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(X)$
\end_inset

 into the Hilbert space of square-integrable functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Other norms are possible, in which case 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(X)$
\end_inset

 has the structure of a Banach space rather than a Hilbert space.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider now a homomorphism of topological spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $g:X\to Y$
\end_inset

.
 This homomorphism induces the pullback 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{*}:\mathcal{F}(Y)\to\mathcal{F}(X)$
\end_inset

 on the algebra of functions, by mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $f\mapsto g^{*}(f)=f\circ g$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ g:Y\to F$
\end_inset

.
 The pullback is a linear operator, in that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
g^{*}(af_{1}+bf_{2})=ag^{*}(f_{1})+bg^{*}(f_{2})\]

\end_inset

That the pullback is linear is easily demonstrated by considering how 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{*}f$
\end_inset

 acts at a point: 
\begin_inset Formula $(g^{*}f)(x)=(f\circ g)(x)=f(g(x))$
\end_inset

 and so the linearity of 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{*}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $af_{1}+bf_{2}$
\end_inset

 follows trivially.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One may construct an analogous mapping, but going in the opposite direction,
 called the push-forward: 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{*}:\mathcal{F}(X)\to\mathcal{F}(Y)$
\end_inset

.
 There are two ways of defining a push-forward.
 One way is to define it in terms of the sheaves of functions on subsets
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 The sheaf-theoretic description is more or less insensitive to the ideas
 of measurability, whereas this is important to the definition of the transfer
 operator, as witnessed by the appearance of the Jacobian determinant in
 equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: transfer-jacobi"

\end_inset

.
 By contrast, the measure-theoretic push-forward captures this desirable
 aspect.
 It may be defined as follows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One endows the spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 with sigma-algebras 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{A})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(Y,\mathcal{B})$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 is the set of subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 obeying the axioms of a sigma-algebra, and similarly for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

.
 A mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $g:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 is called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

measurable
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 if, for all Borel sets 
\begin_inset Formula $B\in\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

, one has the pre-image 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{-1}(B)\in\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 being a Borel set as well.
 Thus, a measurable mapping induces a push-forward on the sigma-algebras:
 that is, one has a push-forward 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{*}:\mathcal{F}(\mathcal{A})\to\mathcal{F}(\mathcal{B})$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $f\mapsto g_{*}(f)=f\circ g^{-1}$
\end_inset

, which is defined by virtue of the measurability of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 The push-forward is a linear operator, in that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
g_{*}(af_{1}+bf_{2})=ag_{*}(f_{1})+bg_{*}(f_{2})\]

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One regains the transfer operator as defined in equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: transfer-jacobi"

\end_inset

 by considering the limiting behavior of the push-forward on progressively
 smaller sets.
 That is, one has
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
The transfer operator is the point-set topology limit of the measure-theoretic
 push-forward.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The proof that follows is informal, so as to keep it simple.
 It is aimed mostly at articulating the language and terminology of measure
 theory.
 The result is none-the-less rigorous, if taken within the confines of the
 definitions presented.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Introduce a measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu:\mathcal{A}\to\mathbb{R}^{+}$
\end_inset

 and analogously 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu:\mathcal{B}\to\mathbb{R}^{+}$
\end_inset

.
 The mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is measure-preserving if 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 is a push-forward of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

, that is, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=g_{*}\mu=\mu\circ g^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 The measure is used to rigorously define integration on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(\mathcal{A})$
\end_inset

 can be informally understood to be integrals, in that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(A)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 may be understood as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
f(A)=\int_{A}\tilde{f}(z)d\mu(z)=\int_{A}\tilde{f}(z)\left|\mu^{\prime}(z)\right|dz\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\mu^{\prime}(x)\right|$
\end_inset

 is to be understood as the Jacobean determinant at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{f}$
\end_inset

 can be understood to be a function that is being integrated over the set
 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, whose integral is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $f(A)$
\end_inset

.
 The value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{f}$
\end_inset

 at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 can be obtained by means of a limit.
 One considers a sequence of 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

, each successively smaller than the last, each containing the point 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 One then has 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\lim_{\overrightarrow{A\ni x}}\,\frac{f(A)}{\mu(A)}=\tilde{f}(x)\]

\end_inset

which can be intuitively proved by considering 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 so small that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{f}$
\end_inset

 is approximately constant over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
f(A)=\int_{A}\tilde{f}(z)d\mu(z)\approx\tilde{f}(x)\int_{A}d\mu=\tilde{f}(x)\mu(A)\]

\end_inset

To perform the analogous limit for the push-forward, one must consider a
 point 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

 and sets 
\begin_inset Formula $B\in\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 containing 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 In what follows, it is now assumed that 
\begin_inset Formula $g:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 is a multi-sheeted countable covering of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 By this it is meant that for any 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 that is not a branch-point, there is a nice neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 such that its pre-image consists of the union of an at most countable number
 of pair-wise disjoint sets.
 That is, for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 not a branch point, and for 
\begin_inset Formula $B\ni y$
\end_inset

 sufficiently small, one may write 
\begin_inset Formula \[
g^{-1}(B)=A_{1}\cup A_{2}\cup\cdots=\bigcup_{j=1}^{k}A_{j}\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is either finite or stands for 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset

, and where 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}\cap A_{j}=\varnothing$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\ne j$
\end_inset

.
 At branch points, such a decomposition may not be possible.
 The axiom of sigma-additivity guarantees that such multi-sheeted covers
 behave just the way one expects integrals to behave: in other words, one
 has 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mu\left(g^{-1}(B)\right)=\mu\left(\bigcup_{j=1}^{k}A_{j}\right)=\sum_{j=1}^{k}\mu\left(A_{j}\right)\]

\end_inset

whenever the collection of 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{j}$
\end_inset

 are pair-wise disjoint.
 Similarly, in order to have the elements 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{F}(\mathcal{A})$
\end_inset

 behave as one expects integrals to behave, one must restrict 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(\mathcal{A})$
\end_inset

 to contain only sigma-additive functions as well, so that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
f\left(g^{-1}(B)\right)=f\left(\bigcup_{j=1}^{k}A_{j}\right)=\sum_{j=1}^{k}f\left(A_{j}\right)\]

\end_inset

As the set 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is taken to be smaller and smaller, the sets 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{j}$
\end_inset

 will become smaller as well.
 Denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j}$
\end_inset

 the corresponding limit point of each 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{j}$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x_{j})=y$
\end_inset

 and the pre-image of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 consists of these points: 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{-1}(y)=\left\{ x_{1},x_{2},\cdots\left|\, g(x_{j})=y\right.\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 One now combines these provisions to write 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\left[g_{*}\tilde{f}\right](y) & = & \lim_{\overrightarrow{B\ni y}}\,\left[\frac{\left(g_{*}f\right)(B)}{\nu(B)}\right]\nonumber \\
 & = & \lim_{\overrightarrow{B\ni y}}\,\left[\frac{\left(f\circ g^{-1}\right)(B)}{\nu(B)}\right]\nonumber \\
 & = & \lim_{\overrightarrow{A_{j}\ni g^{-1}(y)}}\,\frac{f\left(A_{1}\cup A_{2}\cup\cdots\right)}{\nu(B)}\nonumber \\
 & = & \lim_{\overrightarrow{A_{j}\ni g^{-1}(y)}}\,\frac{\sum_{j=1}^{k}f\left(A_{j}\right)}{\nu(B)}\nonumber \\
 & = & \sum_{j=1}^{k}\tilde{f}\left(x_{j}\right)\lim_{\overrightarrow{A_{j}\ni x_{j}}}\,\frac{\mu\left(A_{j}\right)}{\nu(B)}\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

The limit in the last line of this sequence of manipulations may be interpreted
 in two ways, depending on whether one wants to define the measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 to be the push-forward of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

, or not.
 If one does take it to be the push-forward, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=g_{*}\mu$
\end_inset

, then one has 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\lim_{\overrightarrow{A_{j}\ni x_{j}}}\,\frac{\mu\left(A_{j}\right)}{g_{*}\mu(B)}=\frac{1}{\left|g^{\prime}\left(x_{j}\right)\right|}\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|g^{\prime}\left(x_{j}\right)\right|$
\end_inset

 is the Jacobian determinant of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 This last is a standard result of measure theory, and can be intuitively
 proved by noting that 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(A_{j}\right)=B$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\nu\left(B\right)=\int_{A_{j}}g^{\prime}(z)\, d\mu(z)\approx g^{\prime}\left(x_{j}\right)\mu\left(A_{j}\right)\]

\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

small enough
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 Assembling this with the previous result, one has 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left[g_{*}\tilde{f}\right](y)=\sum_{x_{j}\in g^{-1}(y)}\frac{\tilde{f}\left(x_{j}\right)}{\left|g^{\prime}\left(x_{j}\right)\right|}\label{eq:Transfer-point}\end{equation}

\end_inset

which may be easily recognized as equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: transfer-jacobi"

\end_inset

.
 This concludes the proof of the theorem, that the transfer operator is
 just the point-set topology limit of the push-forward.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In simplistic terms, the push-forward can be thought of as a kind of change-of-v
ariable.
 Thus, one should not be surprised by the following lemma, which should
 be recognizable as the Jacobian, from basic calculus.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
(Jacobian) One has 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sum_{x_{j}\in g^{-1}(y)}\frac{1}{\left|g^{\prime}\left(x_{j}\right)\right|}=1\]

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
This follows by taking the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\overrightarrow{A_{j}\ni x_{j}}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{\mu\left(A_{j}\right)}{g_{*}\mu(B)}=\frac{\mu\left(A_{j}\right)}{\sum_{i=1}^{k}\mu\left(A_{i}\right)}\]

\end_inset

 and then summing over 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Corollary
\begin_inset LatexCommand label
name "cor:unit-eigenvec"

\end_inset

The uniform distribution (
\emph on
i.e.

\emph default
 the measure) is an eigenvector of the transfer operator, associated with
 the eigenvalue one.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
This may be proved in two ways.
 From the viewpoint of point-sets, one simply takes 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{f}=\mbox{const.}$
\end_inset

 in equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Transfer-point"

\end_inset

, and applies the lemma above.
 From the viewpoint of the sigma-algebra, this is nothing more than a rephrasing
 of the starting point, that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=g_{*}\mu$
\end_inset

, and then taking the space 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=X$
\end_inset

, so that the push-forward induced by 
\begin_inset Formula $g:X\to X$
\end_inset

 is a measure-preserving map: 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{*}\mu=\mu$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The last corollary is more enlightening when it is turned on its side; it
 implies two well-known theorems, which follow easily in this framework.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Corollary
(Ruelle-Perron-Frobenius theorem).
 All transfer operators are continuous, compact, bounded operators; furthermore,
 they are isometries of Banach spaces.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
This theorem is of course just the Frobenius-Perron theorem, recast in the
 context of measure theory.
 By definition, the measures have unit norm: that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \mu\right\Vert _{1}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \nu\right\Vert _{1}=1$
\end_inset

.
 This is nothing more than the statement that the spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 are measurable: the total volume of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is, by definition, one.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=g_{*}\mu$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert g_{*}\mu\right\Vert _{1}=1$
\end_inset

, and this holds for all possible measures 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\in\mathcal{F}(X)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Recall the definition of a bounded operator.
 Given a linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $T:U\to V$
\end_inset

 between Banach spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is bounded if there exists a constant 
\begin_inset Formula $C<\infty$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert Tu\right\Vert _{V}\le C\left\Vert u\right\Vert _{U}$
\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in U$
\end_inset

.
 But this is exactly the case above, with 
\begin_inset Formula $T=g_{*}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\mathcal{F}(X)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $V=\mathcal{F}(Y)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $C=1$
\end_inset

.
 The norm of a bounded operator is conventionally defined as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left\Vert T\right\Vert =\sup_{u\ne0}\frac{\left\Vert Tu\right\Vert _{V}}{\left\Vert u\right\Vert _{U}}=\sup_{\left\Vert u\right\Vert _{U}\le1}\left\Vert Tu\right\Vert _{V}\]

\end_inset

and so we have the norm of 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{*}$
\end_inset

 being 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert g_{*}\right\Vert =1$
\end_inset

.
 That 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{*}$
\end_inset

 is an isometry follows trivially from 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert g_{*}\mu\right\Vert _{1}=\left\Vert \nu\right\Vert _{1}$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{*}$
\end_inset

 is linear.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The corollary 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "cor:unit-eigenvec"

\end_inset

 can also be treated as a corollary to the Perron-Frobenius theorem: namely,
 that there is at least one vector that corresponds to the maximum eigenvalue
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{*}$
\end_inset

.
 This eigenvector is in fact the Haar measure, as the next theorem shows.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset LatexCommand label
name "thm:Haar-measure"

\end_inset

(Haar measure) For any homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $g:X\to X$
\end_inset

, one may find a measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{*}\mu=\mu$
\end_inset

; that is, every homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 induces a measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is a measure-preserving map.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is ergodic, then the measure is unique.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
By definition, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is a fixed point of 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{*}$
\end_inset

.
 The fixed point exists because 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{*}$
\end_inset

is a bounded operator, and the space of measures is compact, and so a bounded
 operator on a compact space will have a fixed point.
 The existence of the fixed point is given by the Markov-Kakutani theorem
\begin_inset LatexCommand cite
after "p 456"
key "Dunford1957"

\end_inset

.
 The Markov-Kakutani theorem also helps provide the uniqueness condition:
 if there are other push-forwards 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{*}$
\end_inset

 that commute with 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{*}$
\end_inset

, then each such push-forward will also have a fixed point.
 The goal is then to show that when 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is ergodic, there are no other functions 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 that commute with 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 But this follows from the definition of ergodicity: when 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is ergodic, there are no invariant subspaces, and the orbit of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is the whole space.
 As there are no invariant subspaces, there are no operators that can map
 between these subspaces, 
\emph on
i.e.

\emph default
 there are no other commuting operators.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A peculiar special case is worth mentioning: if 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is not ergodic on the whole space, then typically one has that the orbit
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 splits or foliates the measure space into a bunch of pairwise disjoint
 leaves, with 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 being ergodic on each leaf.
 The Markov-Kakutani theorem then implies that there is a distinct fixed
 point 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 in each leaf, and that there is a mapping that takes 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 in one leaf to that in another.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the language of dynamical systems, the push-forward 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{*}$
\end_inset

 is commonly written as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{g}$
\end_inset

, so that one has 
\begin_inset Formula \[
g_{*}=\mathcal{L}_{g}\,:\,\mathcal{F}\left(X\right)\to\mathcal{F}\left(X\right)\]

\end_inset

now being called the transfer operator or the Ruelle-Frobenius-Perron operator.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the language of physics, the fixed point 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

ground state
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of a system.
 When it is unique, then the ground state is not degenerate; when it is
 not unique, then the ground state is said to be degenerate.
 The operator 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{*}$
\end_inset

 is the time-evolution operator of the system; it shows how physical fields
 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{F}(X)$
\end_inset

 over a space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 evolve over time.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is the complex numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

, the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert g_{*}\right\Vert =1$
\end_inset

 is essentially a way of stating that time-evolution is unitary; the Frobenius-P
erron operator is the unitary time-evolution operator of the system.
 What is called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

second quantization
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in physics should be interpreted as the fitting of the space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(X)$
\end_inset

 with a set of basis vectors, together with a formulation of 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{*}$
\end_inset

 in terms of that basis.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Grounding
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To make sense of the discussion above, it is best to ground the symbols
 in concrete terms.
 For the most part, this paper is concerned either with the space 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\Omega$
\end_inset

, the space of strings in two letters, or the spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 that are somehow isomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

.
 This space is a (semi-)infinite product of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}_{2}=\{0,1\}$
\end_inset

; elements 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\in\Omega$
\end_inset

 of this space were values 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=(\sigma_{0},\sigma_{1},\cdots)$
\end_inset

 with each 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{k}\in\mathbb{Z}_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is to be equated with the shift operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

; that is, when 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\Omega$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $g=\tau$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g:X\to X$
\end_inset

 is just 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau:\Omega\to\Omega$
\end_inset

 acting such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau(\sigma_{0},\sigma_{1},\sigma_{2},\cdots)=(\sigma_{1},\sigma_{2},\cdots)$
\end_inset

.
 Curiously, the structure of the space 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 can be understood to be a binary tree: starting at 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{0}$
\end_inset

 one can branch to the left or to the right, to get to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{1}$
\end_inset

, and so on.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, a product space such as this also allows the language of probability
 theory come into play, and this is where things get interesting.
 Product spaces are the natural setting for probability: the element 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\in\Omega$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

random variable
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, and successive values 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{k}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

measurements
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the random variable.
 This is also the manner in which measure theory gets its foot in the door.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The mappings 
\begin_inset Formula $x:\Omega\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 given by eqn 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:binary-number"

\end_inset

 is now seen to be an example of an element of the algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}\left(\Omega\right)$
\end_inset

 introduced in the previous section.
 The mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $y:\Omega\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\mapsto y=?^{-1}\left(x\left(\sigma\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 is another example of an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}\left(\Omega\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Both the maps 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 are invertible on the closed unit interval, establishing a 
\begin_inset Formula $1-1$
\end_inset

 mapping between 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 and the closed unit interval.
 Consider, then, the function 
\begin_inset Formula \[
b=x\circ\tau\circ x^{-1}\]

\end_inset

which maps the unit interval into itself.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $w\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

 be a point in the unit interval; then it is not hard to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $b(w)=2w\mbox{ mod}1$
\end_inset

.
 In the literature, this function is commonly called the Bernoulli shift;
 its corresponding random process is known as the Bernoulli process.
 It is well-known to be ergodic.
 The other function that was considered here was 
\begin_inset Formula \[
A=y\circ\tau\circ y^{-1}\]

\end_inset

Its action on the unit interval has already been given by eqn 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:defn-A"

\end_inset

.
 In a previous section, we have already considered generalizations of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, that is, other functions 
\begin_inset Formula $B:[0,1]\to[0,1]$
\end_inset

, such as, for example, eqn 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:defn-B"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each of these maps 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 can be taken as an example of a map 
\begin_inset Formula $g:X\to X$
\end_inset

, now taking 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 to the unit interval.
 By the previous theorem, each such map 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 induces a push-forward 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{*}=\mathcal{L}_{g}$
\end_inset

, and this push-forward then induces an invariant measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{g}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 For the Bernoulli map 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

, the push-forward 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{b}$
\end_inset

 is introduced in 
\begin_inset LatexCommand cite
key "Gas92,Has92"

\end_inset

, and a detailed study of its eigenvectors is given in 
\begin_inset LatexCommand cite
key "Dri99"

\end_inset

.
 The invariant measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{b}$
\end_inset

 is well-known to be the identity on the unit interval.
 This just means that 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 considered as an ergodic process, is uniformly distributed on the unit
 interval.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The invariant measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{A}$
\end_inset

 has already been established in eqn 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:measure-A"

\end_inset

 as being the Minkowski measure; that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{A}=?^{\prime}$
\end_inset

.
 A previous section already gave specific mechanics for how to take a general,
 differentiable onto-map 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 and define its associated measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{B}$
\end_inset

 as the generalization of eqn 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:piece-product"

\end_inset

.
 The next section introduces the transfer operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{A}$
\end_inset

 corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Flightiness
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To counterbalance the grounding, a brief bit of flightiness as to this process
 is offered up.
 The map 
\begin_inset Formula $g:X\to X$
\end_inset

, can be understood to give the (discrete) time-evolution of a dynamical
 system.
 It is curious to ponder that iterating on 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 can be thought of as the (semi-)infinite chain 
\begin_inset Formula \[
X\begin{array}[b]{c}
g\\
\longrightarrow\end{array}X\begin{array}[b]{c}
g\\
\longrightarrow\end{array}X\begin{array}[b]{c}
g\\
\longrightarrow\end{array}X\begin{array}[b]{c}
g\\
\longrightarrow\end{array}\cdots\]

\end_inset

and so any particular 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

, together with an initial state 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

, can be interpreted as selecting a particular sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{0},x_{1},x_{2},\ldots)$
\end_inset

 out of the (semi-)infinite product space 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=X\times X\times X\times\cdots$
\end_inset

.
 The set membership function now defines a measure on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

: sets that contain sequences 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{0},x_{1},x_{2},\ldots)$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{k+1}=g\left(x_{k}\right)$
\end_inset

 will have a non-zero measure, all others will have a measure of zero.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This now begs the question: what sort of operators might have this measure
 as their invariant measure? Which of these operators might be push-forwards?
 What would they be a push-forward of? Last but not least, all of the spaces
 under discussion are metric spaces, and so it would be curious to know
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

what else is close by
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 These questions are not entirely idle.
 The product space 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 can be seen to be 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

space-time
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

; by analogy to the binary tree, the structure of this space-time is once-again
 seen to be branching; infinitely branching in this case.
 But such branching is already seen in physics: this is nothing other than
 the many-worlds interpretation of quantum mechanics, where, at each moment
 of time, the universe is seen to split into an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

infinite number of copies of itself
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 The many-worlds branching structure is not well-explored or well-understood,
 although it can illuminate problems of quantum measurement and wave-function
 collapse.
 One such curious problem is the so-called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Mott problem
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 The question that is posed by the Mott problem is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

why does the spherically symmetric wave function of an emitted alpha-ray
 always leave a straight-line track in a Wilson cloud chamber?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 The answer was given by Heisenberg and Mott in 1929; it can be re-interpreted
 in the context of the current formulation as a statement that straight-line
 tracks have a significant measure in this branching space-time, as they
 all correspond to sets that contain the point that is the spherical wave-functi
on, and no other sets do.
 But this is just an impressionistic daydream, lacking rigor; the hope is
 that it motivates further study.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Twisted Bernoulli Operator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We know consider the transfer operator or push-forward of the mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 It resembles the Bernoulli shift, but is twisted in a curious way; it is
 a continued-fraction analog of the Bernoulli shift.
 It is straight-forward to write it down; it is very simply 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\mathcal{L}_{A}f\right]\left(y\right)=\frac{1}{\left(1+y\right)^{2}}f\left(\frac{y}{1+y}\right)+\frac{1}{\left(2-y\right)^{2}}f\left(\frac{1}{2-y}\right)\]

\end_inset

This expression is easily obtained by starting with eqn 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: transfer-jacobi"

\end_inset

 and substituting in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 from eqn 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:defn-A"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Of course, the Minkowski measure is an eigenfunction of the twisted Bernoulli
 shift; that is, one has 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{A}?^{\prime}=?^{\prime}\]

\end_inset

This can be seen in several ways: The Minkowski measure was constructed
 as the Haar measure induced by 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, and so by theorem 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:Haar-measure"

\end_inset

, of course this identity must hold.
 But it can also be validated by more pedestrian methods: simply plug in
 the measure, and turn the crank, making use of the self-similarity relation
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:meas-self-sim"

\end_inset

 as needed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Other eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{A}$
\end_inset

 are readily found.
 Consider the functions 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{f}$
\end_inset

 as previously defined in 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:defn-P_f"

\end_inset

.
 The action of the twisted Bernoulli shift on 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{f}$
\end_inset

 is readily computed, and is given by 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{A}P_{f}=P_{f}\cdot\mathcal{L}_{A}f\]

\end_inset

We've already observed that when 
\begin_inset Formula $f=A^{\prime}/2$
\end_inset

, that one has 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{A}\frac{A^{\prime}}{2}=1\]

\end_inset

so that 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{A^{\prime}/2}=?^{\prime}$
\end_inset

.
 Another, linearly independent function which satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{A}f=1$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
C\left(y\right)=\begin{cases}
\frac{1}{3\left(1-y\right)^{3}} & \mbox{ for }0\le y\le\frac{1}{2}\\
\frac{1}{3y^{3}} & \mbox{ for }\frac{1}{2}\le y\le1\end{cases}\]

\end_inset

 that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{A}C=1$
\end_inset

.
 The collection of all 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 which satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{A}f=1$
\end_inset

 is large, but is easily specified.
 Let
\begin_inset Formula \[
f\left(y\right)=\begin{cases}
f_{0}\left(y\right) & \mbox{ for }0\le y\le\frac{1}{2}\\
f_{1}\left(y\right) & \mbox{ for }\frac{1}{2}\le y\le1\end{cases}\]

\end_inset

then, given any, arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{0}$
\end_inset

, solving for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{A}f=1$
\end_inset

 results in 
\begin_inset Formula \[
f_{1}\left(y\right)=\frac{1}{y^{2}}-\frac{1}{\left(3y-1\right)^{2}}f_{0}\left(\frac{2x-1}{3x-1}\right)\]

\end_inset

Such 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 are properly scaled; that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\left(\Omega\right)=1$
\end_inset

.
 Because of the projective relationship between the functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and the normalization 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\left(\Omega\right)$
\end_inset

, it appears that this technique will result in only in eigenfunctions 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{f}$
\end_inset

 with eigenvalue 1.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Keep in mind that while 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{f+h}\ne P_{f}+P_{h}$
\end_inset

, such a relationship does hold in the logarithmic sense: 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{fh}=P_{f}P_{h}$
\end_inset

, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 can be construed to be a (logarithmic) homomorphism of Banach spaces.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Gauss-Kuzmin-Wirsing Operator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Gauss-Kuzmin-Wirsing (GKW) operator is the transfer operator of the
 Gauss map 
\begin_inset Formula $h(x)=1/x-\left\lfloor 1/x\right\rfloor $
\end_inset

.
 Denoting this operator as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{G}$
\end_inset

, it acts on a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left[\mathcal{L}_{G}f\right](x)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{\left(x+n\right)^{2}}\, f\left(\frac{1}{x+n}\right)\label{eq:gkw}\end{equation}

\end_inset

It has a well-known eigenfunction, noted by Gauss, corresponding to eigenvalue
 one, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $1/(1+y)$
\end_inset

.
 It is also relatively straightforward to observe that the Minkowski measure
 is also an eigenfunction, also corresponding to eigenvalue one.
 This is readily seen by differentiating the Question Mark: one has 
\begin_inset Formula \[
?\left(\frac{1}{n+x}\right)=\frac{1}{2^{n-1}}-\frac{?\left(x\right)}{2^{n}}\]

\end_inset

and so also 
\begin_inset Formula \[
?^{\prime}\left(\frac{1}{n+x}\right)=\frac{\left(x+n\right)^{2}}{2^{n}}?^{\prime}\left(x\right)\]

\end_inset

This can be directly inserted into eqn 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:gkw"

\end_inset

 to very easily find that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{G}?^{\prime}=?^{\prime}\]

\end_inset

This result immediately suggests that the lattice model methods can be applied
 to find other eigenfunctions.
 (The 3-adic Question mark, at least as defined above, does not have this
 property, suggesting, perhaps, that a different 3-adic Question Mark should
 be formulated).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The GKW operator is tied by various identities to the twisted Bernoulli
 operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{A}$
\end_inset

.
 These are explicitly given by 
\begin_inset LatexCommand cite
key "Iso03"

\end_inset

; they can be crudely summarized by saying that these identities are the
 operator analogues of Denjoy's explicit summation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:direct ? fun defn"

\end_inset

.
 In these rough terms, the Bernoulli shift chops off one digit of a binary
 number at a time; these may be in turn re-assembled to form the GKW operator.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The action of the GKW operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{G}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{f}$
\end_inset

 is not at all tidy; the result that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{G}?^{\prime}=?^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 appears to be entirely due to the special form of 
\begin_inset Formula $f=A^{\prime}/2$
\end_inset

.
 This is perhaps no surprise.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Other fractal eigenvectors for the GKW can be constructed by a technique
 entirely parallel to the construction of the 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{f}$
\end_inset

; one only has to use a different lattice model.
 For this model, construct 
\begin_inset Formula \[
R_{f}\left(y\right)=\frac{1}{Z\left(\Omega\right)}\prod_{k=0}^{\infty}f\circ D_{k}\left(y\right)\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{k+1}=D_{k}\circ D$
\end_inset

 is function iteration, and
\begin_inset Formula \[
D\left(y\right)=\begin{cases}
\frac{1-y}{y} & \mbox{ for }\frac{1}{2}<y\le1\\
\cdots & \cdots\\
\frac{1-ny}{y} & \mbox{ for }\frac{1}{n+1}<y\le\frac{1}{n}\\
\cdots & \cdots\end{cases}\]

\end_inset

for positive integers 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 This multi-branched 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 has the property that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
D\left(\frac{1}{x+n}\right)=x\]

\end_inset

for all integer values of 
\begin_inset Formula $n\ge1$
\end_inset

.
 Applying the GKW operator to 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{f}$
\end_inset

 results in 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{G}R_{f}=R_{f}\mathcal{L}_{G}f\]

\end_inset

in analogy to the twisted Bernoulli operator.
 The means for finding solutions to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{G}f=1$
\end_inset

 proceeds analogously.
 Thus, let 
\begin_inset Formula \[
f\left(y\right)=\begin{cases}
f_{1}\left(y\right) & \mbox{ for }\frac{1}{2}<y\le1\\
\cdots & \cdots\\
f_{n}\left(y\right) & \mbox{ for }\frac{1}{n+1}<y\le\frac{1}{n}\\
\cdots & \cdots\end{cases}\]

\end_inset

Then the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{G}f=1$
\end_inset

 established only a single constraint between these 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}$
\end_inset

's: all but one may be freely chosen.
 As an example, consider 
\begin_inset Formula \[
f_{n}\left(y\right)=\frac{a_{n}}{y^{2}}\]

\end_inset

Then the resulting 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{G}f=1$
\end_inset

 provided that the constants 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}$
\end_inset

 satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}a_{n}=1\]

\end_inset

This construction shows that the space of fractal eigenfunctions of the
 GKW operator is very large; but, as before, all of these eigenfunctions
 appear to be non-decaying, corresponding to eigenvalue 1.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Conclusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The principal results of this note are the statistical distribution of equation
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:integral"

\end_inset

, which allows numerical explorations of the binary trees to be explicitly
 equated to the Minkowski measure, and equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:piece-product"

\end_inset

, which shows that the seemingly intractable Minkowski measure can be built
 up out of analytic functions in a regular way.
 A sufficient amount of formal theory is developed to show how to root this
 measure in a foundational apparatus, thus enabling various basic manipulations
 on it to be safely performed.
 Of these, the most notable was to expose the transfer operator as a push-forwar
d on a Banach space, leading to an interpretation of the Minkowski measure
 as a invariant measure, a Haar measure, induced by a dynamical map.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An important theme is the tension between the natural topology on the real
 number line, and the much finer 'weak topology' on the product space 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{\omega}$
\end_inset

.
 It should be clear that the fine topology is the source for a broad variety
 for fractal, self-similar phenomena.
 The use of the measure extension theorem allows these fine-grained fractal
 phenomena to manifest themselves onto the natural topology; the Minkowski
 measure serves as a non-trivial yet still simple example of such a manifestatio
n.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, various open problems remain.
 The most important of these surrounds the observation that transfer operators
 have a discrete spectrum, when the space of functions is restricted to
 a much smaller set, for instance, when it is restricted to the set of square-in
tegrable functions, or to the set of polynomials.
 In some cases, this spectrum can be obtained exactly; this has been done
 for the case of the Bernoulli operator 
\begin_inset LatexCommand cite
key "Gas92,Has92,Dri99"

\end_inset

.
 More generally, obtaining this spectrum seems almost intractable; here,
 the prototypical example is the GKW operator.
 Of course, both the eigenvalues and the eigenvectors of the GKW operator
 can be computed numerically; however, there is no articulation or framework
 within which to talk about them and to manipulate them; they remain opaque.
 They seem to be mere holomorphic functions (by definition!) and oscillatory,
 of course; but there is not yet a way of writing down their power series
 directly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, the open problem is to develop a technical framework that will identify
 the discrete eigenvalue spectrum of a transfer operator, and to directly
 provide expressions for the holomorphic functions which are their eigenvectors.
 Such a framework would be of broad utility.
 
\end_layout

